Allow me to unfold this memory map of the city where I was born and lived for 29 years. Today, it is so foreign that even a month or two ago is something to try to remember.
Was Wuhan made of gold at that time? Yeah, well, at least the memory's gold.
Across the street from 50 meters there are braving the white gas of the breakfast stall, hot dry noodles in the bowl, bean skin in the pot, wine is still in the cup, tears have not been swallowed into the stomach, people are busy preparing for the new year.
Preserved Fish and preserved meat is long gone, and the New Year is a seafood treat -- a nine-knot shrimp the size of a hand, a bread crab that resembles a woodfish, or an orange-red Atlantic fish called a Florida. Housewives Fumble through their recipes, steaming fish with their heads open, as if the city had not yet eaten them, as if it were an internet economy import.
Children who have grown up speaking mandarin have gone home from all over the world, passing migrant workers and college students at airport stations; adults who have grown up speaking Wuhan are busy being forced to fulfill a somewhat weary obligation to celebrate the New Year.
In short, Wuhan at that time was no different from most big cities in China.

Similar to "comfort" and "Bashi" in Chengdu, "Qi" and "Lao Pao er" in Beijing, "Lao Ke LE" and "Shang Zhi Jiao" in Shanghai, Wuhan has also been dubbed as "a river lake" and "a wharf" , which are extremely charming and easy to get capital.
But what exactly is the "rivers and lakes" and "Docks" ? Were the bodies of several battle victims permanently displayed under the bronze statue of Sun Yat-sen in the heart of the city in the summer of 1966, or were the incisions in the slang that circulated in the 1980s and 1990s as the Down to the Countryside Movement returned to the city?
Maybe the "quacks" and "docks" just don't talk properly.
When a motorcycle driver tells you, put a dollar in your hand, that means he wants 10 pieces of Florida, in the 1990s, in a heavy industrial city where housing prices hadn't yet driven the economy, the dignity of the people was gone, the money was in Guangzhou, in Wenzhou, and yet here, but popular this frivolous, to appear to lift heavy if light;
When an outsider asked the early-bird stall owner how much a bowl of porridge cost, the boss said, "one dime. It's also possible that quack and dock are the smoke-filled air conditioning of the Old Town Arcade, that the soda bottle cap has been pried open, that you're Hat-trick Owen on the screen, and you're scared, even Huan dared not raise his voice for fear that he would come up with a hand: "Young Man, do you have any money on you? "

Like the childhood hot dry noodles, only put sesame sauce and absolutely no brine, outsiders feel dry, astringent, difficult to swallow, but parents eat in high spirits.
Holding a knife and fork, eager to go to the Imaginary City Development Dividend feast, eagerly launched against Wuhan and other cities, and concluded that it is no doubt that Wuhan is the hottest new line, the only immediate adjustment is house prices, which should be higher and more metropolitan -- What was it like, I thought for years before that.
People I know and I still go to the old shop to eat raw beef. There is a pot of beef broth in which people can lie down and take a bath. The shop staff take turns to add water, MSG and beef bones, but that pot hasn't stopped boiling for 24 hours. A penniless drunkard burns a bowl of beef liver, formerly $3.50 beef noodles, now seventeen -- cheaper than mcdonald's, and more expensive than mcdonald's -- as if it were still edible.

For a while, I went to the south China Seafood Market three or five times a week.
Every year during the crayfish or hairy crab season, people shop in a row of storefronts across the street, and like most of the mainland's seafood markets, the area is notorious for underweight.
The Alley of Back Street is a wholesale business. I have patronized almost every unknown storefront. There are well-known vendors who can guess the owner's hometown by the kinds of seafood they sell. MIICHTHYS Miiuy, Yellow Croaker and pomfret are from Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces, yellow Wings, sand tip, mud Menglai from Fujian and Guangdong.
I often go to a seafood restaurant called "Tianfei" , which has excellent sweet potato powder, oysters, Xinghua powder and Gushan old wine. The boss's family is Fuzhou horsetail people, kind-hearted and easy-going, always making tea, often wipe zero, have bought a house in the Wuhan suburb.
Another frequent shop is called "Xiangzhi" . The name comes from a small town in the owner's hometown of Shishi in southern Fujian. It is common to see recently dead grouper fish being pulled out of a fish tank. The owner will wave his hand impatiently, "TAKE THE $20! " Like you don't care about retail. At a time when Taobao's fresh food distribution was underdeveloped, the shops of the south China seafood market were the only way for people from the coastal region to make a living in Wuhan, like the Ho Chi Minh trail or the Hump Route, to get food from home.
Some Alley has sells the snake, I once bought to use to boil the soup, the boss directly wears the glove to catch, chops off the snake's head to chop the chopping piece. These snakes are breeding, there is a very mature industrial chain, Taobao has sold, four or five years ago, a small Zaoci snake but sixty yuan.
The only thing I can't accept is that there have been people in this market who have killed a live dog in the street, or drowned a cat and disguised it as rabbit. A decade-long tug-of-war between stallholders and journalists and nearby residents has been determined by the growth of pet protection groups. No one dares to sell dog meat in public these days, and if you do, the vendor unknowingly pulls out a frozen dog leg, as if it were food from an unknown source.
At the end of the alley by the snake stand, I had seen something like a wolf cub or a badger, not big, in a small iron cage, with bright eyes, more alive than the fish and bullfrogs around it, and I tried to squeeze the thick railing, "Watch your mouth! " The stall owner exclaimed, "it's a real contraband, and it's the most game-defining ingredient I've ever seen. ".
As for eating bats, I had never heard of them growing up.

At first, public opinion focused on the seafood market, and I supported it, but I also joined in the scolding: First, eating wild animals is of course bad and should be promoted vigorously; second, the owner of the South China Seafood Market is indeed a bloody millionaire who made his fortune in the 1990s, like many others, he retired and disappeared into the history of the city.
But it makes no sense to attribute the origin of the virus to the fact that the people of Wuhan Love Venison, and to give it a causal inevitability. Wuhan people do not "love to eat game" atmosphere, the south China seafood market is just a southern city again common, fish and dragons mixed wholesale market, is not illegal. Moreover, it is absurd to think that a city that bans the slaughter of live chickens because of bird flu is full of game.
It is true that there was once a night-time gathering place in the city called "Game Street" , where the main dish was actually a roast chicken, and what looked like pheasants were kept together in the cage with the rooster, which I later learned, it's just a breed of guinea-fowl, Muscovy ducks, used for promotional purposes.
Most customers don't order Guinea fowl or Muscovy ducks, and a few of them live in cages for at least three months -- as I observed when I was in elementary school, most customers order a rooster and kill it on the side of the road. The people who come to eat are mostly men, doing relatively "social" jobs, building trades, grass-roots government agencies, and so on. The illusion of eating game, curiosity, mixed with Braggadocio, mixed together, is the next food or APHRODISIAC. Of course, these people are not bad people, but also in life once called uncle uncle.
About 10 years ago, Game Street was banned, not for selling game, but for disturbing people.

Many people have forgotten what Wuhan looked like a few days before the blockade, and I also remember.
The reason I wear a mask is that I have a fashion mask from a friend at home, and of course it's important to be reminded.
On January 12, my friend asked me to read in the library, and when I met him, he was wearing a standard N95, a very boring one, with a rubber band around the back of his head like a gas mask, and he didn't take it off while he was reading. I immediately began to think to myself, 'hey, I'm so full of Shit, I'm sure I'm not the only one, wearing a standard N95 mask indoors in Wuhan before January 16,2020 was quite a sight, people passing by would give him a surprised look or two.
"It's kind of scary, " he told me. "You'd better wear it, too. "
Over the years, Wuhan has never had a tradition of wearing masks seasonally because of the smog. People who wear masks like this are either sick, or they think other people are sick, or they're sick. In Wuhan, it's called a Florida -- a Florida potato, meaning any person who wears a mask in a library all the time will be treated as a Yam.
A few days later, the corresponding Emoji, widely circulated on social media, read, "the whole world thinks China is an epidemic area, the whole Chinese people think Wuhan is an epidemic area, and the people of Wuhan are still having a happy New Year party. ". At first, the people of Wuhan did feel offended. They felt that having a virus in their city was humiliating, an insult, a smear from others, and they needed to speak out to clarify, so most people choose to say "all is well" in their own way, a logic that has endured through the ages -- as if they were always in denial about what makes them uncomfortable.
Then, "the wharf culture" has been proposed once again.
But no culture is keen on catching infectious diseases or getting into trouble with money. The point is, you got ta go to the pharmacy, you got Ta Act, and the information that the average citizen gets before the lockdown isn't enough to act.
From "limited" to "closed" period, the vast majority of citizens have not received any advice, warning and reminder, before not know what to do, after nothing to do.

The day before the lockdown, a friend of mine, a programmer in California, said he was going to send me some medicine, brought back from the states. I thought about it and replied, "No, I'm afraid to die. "
The programmer went back to Wuhan on New Year's Day for the New Year. He had originally agreed to go together to eat hot beef noodles. Later he dared not eat it. He said that he would have a cup of coffee. He also failed to drink the coffee. He hastily bought a plane ticket back to the United States on the 30th day of the New Year and lost 7,000 yuan.

The day before the lockdown, the programmer had already packed his bags to go to bed. The next day, after lunch with his family, he left Wuhan. He bought a Delta flight ticket from Wuhan to Tokyo to Los Angeles. When he received the message, he was completely lost.
For How long? Maybe 15 days? Who knows, it might affect work in the United States? He knocks on the door to wake his parents, and it takes the family about 0.5 seconds to make the decision for him -- to walk, to drive, to buy a new ticket.
The programmer is still rummaging through the trunk for the final count, the car downstairs has started, his mother sat in the car urged him: "Be careful of the airport high-speed closure. "
When I went out, there was nothing unusual on the street. It was like the early morning of a normal year. When I got on the airport expressway, I found that many taxis on the road were rushing there. The programmer bought a ticket for Wuhan to fly to Los Angeles via Shanghai at 8:00. After I bought it, I refreshed it, and they were sold out.
The airport doesn't look crowded, blast-proof security doesn't have to wait in line, and the programmers are waiting at the check-in counter. The two would-be fugitives were not at ease until the announcement of boarding.

For the first two or three weeks, I know many people in Wuhan who turn on social media and say, I x, I x, I x, until they get to a request for help and stop and say, "I, X... "
It was probably a cry for help from your friends and family, and you didn't know anything about it until now.
Death is fatalistic in many places. In Wuhan, the way it was known before, was by wreaths downstairs, and families had a dawn that could wake their neighbors with a band. But the virus changed all that, and it had the worst part of both illness and accident.
Patients suffer the possibility of death. Families suffer the passivity of their loved ones before they die. When you ask for help online, you have to explain something to someone. My friend Jia, who works in the media, was also hit. She didn't tweet, and though she could do it on the day of the attack, she decided to wait for community notification and stay home. Without a bed, on the 10th day, the old woman fainted. Feeling hopeless, she began asking for help online, hoping to be admitted to a hospital and to buy an oxygen machine.
I had an oxygen machine, but no one could drive it. One of the best comments was to suggest that she buy her own oxygen-generating material, stick it in a water bottle and make her own oxygen machine, "everyone who raises and watches fish knows that, " said the netizen. I really admire his humor.
I listened to the recording of her phone call with the community, a pointless and frustrating back and forth, and I could see the clerk's face in front of me, not particularly angry, raising his voice just to take the initiative, it's like turning down a person applying for a living wage or a peddler whose car has been impounded. Soon, I began to suspect that I was sick, too, with a sore throat.
I was acutely aware of the tiniest changes in my body every day, and kept trying to swallow to see if this one was any more painful than the last. He inhales heavily, feels his heart starting to colic, and takes his temperature every 20 minutes. To make matters worse, my thighs are starting to swell, and I haven't exercised in a long time.
I couldn't tell my mom, I couldn't tell my friends. I can only think of all the people I met on the subway, in the library, in the market, everyone who met me, everyone who touched me. My best friend's mother was worse off than I was, had a cough for so long that she went to the pharmacy to buy Oseltamivir herself -- Everyone knows hospitals are easier places to cross.

Then there's the matter of food.
I probably have more food in my freezer than 90% of the people in Wuhan. It's a frozen brisket my mother bought with her neighbor a year ago. I don't know if it's Uruguayan or Brazilian Zombie meat.
At one point, I laughed at the idea of a supermarket with a cold chain that delivers fresh, sour beef, and a price hike in the new year. It's a bargain for hoarders and hungry people. But now that the city's been sealed, it's all changed.
I nearly smashed my mother's phone when she had to leave for work; I ventured out to deliver food and face masks to friends and scavengers, where my mother was also sighing. In short, everyone agrees that going out is a form of irresponsibility toward other family members, preferring to save food rather than buy groceries.
As the leftovers were slowly and irreversibly consumed, I began to realize something old common sense: Eggs weren't nearly as big as meat. Fifty eggs, two for a family of three, would last just over a week, when the eggs were half gone, I began to scrape the remaining liquid off the eggshell membrane with my hands.
Cooking techniques are also worth studying. Boiled eggs don't add food to the meal, and they are the first to be eliminated. The luxury of throwing away egg yolks at the gym seems like a lifetime ago. Scrambled eggs have no food to go with them, and scrambled eggs never seem like a proper meal. The most common meal is steamed eggs, which, like clam stew eggs, are sprinkled with scallions and poured with oil, an Egg can bring a bowl of rice.
Shanghai residents later learned from the experience: Braised eggs, when the main dish is cooked, add soy sauce and sugar, two people can send an egg bowl of rice, the role of the individual units of the egg to play to the extreme, is indeed the ability of others.
Instead of fresh pork, I tried soaking it in Bacon water, trying to revive it. It tasted like pork marinated in Baking Soda, tender and layered, but couldn't soak it for long. Once it was in the fridge for a week, it's not that different from Qin Shi Huang's grave.

The food shortage represents, more than anything, a deterioration in expectations about the future, because not being able to buy food to go hungry or eat instant noodles is not the same as eating instant noodles for a meal or two to lose weight or working too hard. Soon the queue was longer than two blocks, everyone was more polite, no one cut in line, some people found that they forgot to bring money to go up to get, before and after the people also agree that the basic maintenance of the interval of 2 meters. The old people were talking to each other. "It's like buying groceries when we were young. "
The first time, I used enough to buy shares, after the money, the staff shouted: "Meat is still enough for 1 person! " I think, do not want to leave 1 catty of meat to the elderly behind? So I took it home, feeling like I hadn't had fresh meat in over a month.
The second time, when it was my turn, there weren't many meat dishes left. I bought only one fish, leaving my share of meat and eggs to others. I was also reminded of the accusations made in the Internet court against Wuhan residents for not stocking up on enough food, it may not be the smartest thing to do.
I live on Jianghan road, the traditional heart of Wuhan, and the shopping scene that day was featured on the Hubei News as an excellent example of community support. I wasn't the best, if not the worst, at least not by a long shot.

Epilogue

"Wuhan People" is a wonderful word.
Sometimes, it is the heroic Wuhan people, when the Heroic Wuhan people tell the plight of the time, become a giant baby. It's been 50 days since the city closed, and there are no giant babies in Wuhan, only people who can buy 40 yuan a piece of fish and 50 yuan a Jin of meat, and those who can't buy 40 yuan a piece of fish and 50 yuan a Jin of meat. It is not the virus that is not contagious, but common sense, empathy and people's joys and sorrows.
Maybe one day each of us will be like this, sitting in a room, facing someone else's dilemma, tapping away on the keyboard, as if I knew we were just sitting on the bench, that one day it would be our turn to play, but before we do, we should know what happened to each other, and, above all, live.
A few days ago, a California programmer bought a truckload of cans, Indian long stalks, and Quinoa that looked like it would last six months, and he said that California might have to stock up and decide, like me, never to go out again.
Once again, we reminisced about our high school days, when we didn't know each other, but we found that we had eaten the same hot and dry noodles and drank the same milk tea, the students were separated by a wall and did not know each other. I would go to the alley across the street to smoke cigarettes, play cards, fall in love, copy homework, or see if there was a fight going on; he would only go to the stationer's or the newsstand on the street to see if there were any new books by Antony and Qijin, or skyping with your classmates about action figures.
I mean, your school never plays in the alley across the street.
The programmer said, that's them. I go there all the time.
I mean, like, deep in the ghetto over there?
He said, "sort of. ".
We talked a lot that day, about the memory, spirit, smell of Wuhan, and the time we spent together. There are times when the ocean is closer than the wall.

The programmer went back to Wuhan on New Year's Day for the New Year. He had originally agreed to go together to eat hot beef noodles. Later he dared not eat it. The programmer is still rummaging through the trunk for the final count, the car downstairs has started, his mother sat in the car urged him: "Be careful of the airport high-speed closure. "
When I went out, there was nothing unusual on the street. It was like the early morning of a normal year. When I got on the airport expressway, I found that many taxis on the road were rushing there. From the consumption level, the epidemic area of Wuhan may be one of the most developed areas in the world, 40 blocks of smoke has no longer existed, convenience stores were required to close all. We all know it's actually open, and the owner only does business with people who have his Wechat, so the owner's wechat becomes a hot commodity.
Early in the morning, a bag of cigarettes and cans of instant noodles came over the wall and was handed from one end of the iron fence to the other, the rent will be through the roof.

Local shopping is difficult, out-of-town friends can only send in things by brains or chance.
"Can you sell me a box of Pien Tze Huang? " Chen told a clerk one day.
The other guy didn't get it. "Box? "
For Zhangzhou people who have friends in Hubei Province, the most urgent material at the end of February is the packing related to Pien Tze Huang. Boxes, boxes and even bags are equivalent to vouchers for sending things to Hubei Province. Chen stayed in Wuhan to work after graduation, and when the epidemic began, many of his friends were trapped at home, without food or clothing, or even shampoo, toilet paper or facial cleanser.
At first, SF limited the sending of face masks to the Hubei region, but the sending of food and supplies also turned a blind eye. Most of the time, the "face masks" became a cover. Later, the rules were changed to send only medicines, and must be a local Chinese medicine listed company Pien Tze Huang's drugs.
But when she managed to get hold of the box of Pien Tze Huang, the couriers in the county said they would not send anything until they reached the city of Zhangzhou.
| City blocks blocked by water horses (photo by the author)
The symbol of the end of the chaotic moment is the community speaker that finally changed from "according to the national laws and regulations on infectious diseases, this community is under closed management" to "residents comrades hurry down to buy vegetables, fish supply. ". About 10 days and half a month will be supplied once, have to run downstairs as fast as possible, each person limit to buy 2 catties of pork, 2 fish, 60 eggs, 50 catties of pork, about 3 and a half catties of grass carp 40 yuan, probably twice as expensive as usual, but it's a bargain compared to the ridiculous prices circulating on the Internet.

Soon the queue was longer than two blocks, everyone was more polite, no one cut in line, some people found that they forgot to bring money to go up to get, before and after the people also agree that the basic maintenance of the interval of 2 meters. The old people were talking to each other. "It's like buying groceries when we were young. "
The first time, I used enough to buy shares, after the money, the staff shouted: "Meat is still enough for 1 person! " I think, do not want to leave 1 catty of meat to the elderly behind? So I took it home, feeling like I hadn't had fresh meat in over a month.
The second time, when it was my turn, there weren't many meat dishes left. I bought only one fish, leaving my share of meat and eggs to others. I was also reminded of the accusations made in the Internet court against Wuhan residents for not stocking up on enough food, it may not be the smartest thing to do.
I live on Jianghan road, the traditional heart of Wuhan, and the shopping scene that day was featured on the Hubei News as an excellent example of community support. I wasn't the best, if not the worst, at least not by a long shot.

Epilogue

"Wuhan People" is a wonderful word.
Sometimes, it is the heroic Wuhan people, when the Heroic Wuhan people tell the plight of the time, become a giant baby. It's been 50 days since the city closed, and there are no giant babies in Wuhan, only people who can buy 40 yuan a piece of fish and 50 yuan a Jin of meat, and those who can't buy 40 yuan a piece of fish and 50 yuan a Jin of meat. It is not the virus that is not contagious, but common sense, empathy and people's joys and sorrows.
Maybe one day each of us will be like this, sitting in a room, facing someone else's dilemma, tapping away on the keyboard, as if I knew we were just sitting on the bench, that one day it would be our turn to play, but before we do, we should know what happened to each other, and, above all, live.
A few days ago, a California programmer bought a truckload of cans, Indian long stalks, and Quinoa that looked like it would last six months, and he said that California might have to stock up and decide, like me, never to go out again.
Once again, we reminisced about our high school days, when we didn't know each other, but we found that we had eaten the same hot and dry noodles and drank the same milk tea, the students were separated by a wall and did not know each other. I would go to the alley across the street to smoke cigarettes, play cards, fall in love, copy homework, or see if there was a fight going on; he would only go to the stationer's or the newsstand on the street to see if there were any new books by Antony and Qijin, or skyping with your classmates about action figures.
I mean, your school never plays in the alley across the street.
The programmer said, that's them. I go there all the time.
I mean, like, deep in the ghetto over there?
He said, "sort of. ".
We talked a lot that day, about the memory, spirit, smell of Wuhan, and the time we spent together. There are times when the ocean is closer than the wall.
